ffolk, England"},"en":{"about 1353–1408":"about 1353–1408","1357–1421":"1357–1421","1379–1443":"1379–1443","1379–Female":"1379–Deceased","1402–1491":"1402–1491","1353–1408":"1353–1408","1402":"1402","1379":"1379","1357":"1357","1443":"1443","1421":"1421","1353":"1353","about 1378":"about 1378","1382":"1382","1408":"1408","1491":"1491","about 1353":"about 1353","Thornham Magna, Suffolk, England":"Thornham Magna, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Stoke by Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Stoke by Ipswich, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Blyant","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Celtic personal name <i>Brian</i> (from <i>brigo-</i> ‘high’ + the suffix <i>-ant-</i>), with excrescent <i>-t</i>. Breton bearers of this name were among the Normans who invaded England in 1066. They went on to settle in Ireland in the 12th century, where the name mingled with the native Irish form <i>Briain</i> (see   O'Brien  ). The latter had also been borrowed, as <i>Brján</i>, by the Vikings, who introduced it independently into northwestern England before the Norman Conquest.","Breton: very rare variant of   Briant   (see   Briand  ) and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this.","History: The American poet William Cullen Bryant (1794–1878) came of a New England family, being descended from Stephen Bryant, who had settled in Plymouth Colony in 1632."],"variants":[{"name":"Brian","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Bryant  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Briain</b>, see   O'Brien  .","French: unflattering nickname from Old Occitan <i>brian</i> ‘mite, maggot’, by extension <i>brimborion</i>, possibly denoting a very small man."]},{"name":"Bryan","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Bryant  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Briain</b>, see   O'Brien  ."]},{"name":"Briant","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Andre, Laure.","English: altered form of   Bryant  .","Breton: variant of   Briand  ."]},{"name":"O'Brien","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Dermot, Liam, Brigid, Declan, Donovan, John Patrick, Kieran, Colm, Donal, Brennan, Caitlin.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Briain</b> ‘descendant of <i>Brian</i>’, a personal name probably based on the element <i>bre-</i> ‘hill’, with the transferred sense ‘eminence’, i.e. ‘exalted one’. See also   Bryan  . In Ireland there has also been some confusion with   O'Byrne   (see   Byrne  ).","History: This name is borne in particular by one of the greatest of Irish septs, descendants of Brian Boru, who rose to the high kingship of Ireland in 1002."]},{"name":"Bryon","meanings":["English: variant of   Bryant  .","Irish (Sligo): from <b>Ó Briain</b>, see   O'Brien  ."]}]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":29,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Simon Blyant was born about 1353, in Thornham Magna, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. He married Agnes de Bresworth about 1378, in Stoke by Ipswich, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 3 daughters. He died in 1408, in Stoke by Ipswich, Suffolk, England, at the age of 56, and was buried in Stoke by Ipswich, Suffolk, England."},"et":{"about 1353–1408":"umbes 1353–1408","1357–1421":"1357–1421","1379–1443":"1379–1443","1379–Female":"1379–Surnud","1402–1491":"1402–1491","1353–1408":"1353–1408","1402":"1402","1379":"1379","1357":"1357","1443":"1443","1421":"1421","1353":"1353","about 1378":"umbes 1378","1382":"1382","1408":"1408","1491":"1491","about 1353":"umbes 1353","Thornham Magna, Suffolk, England":"Thornham Magna, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Stoke by Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Stoke by Ipswich, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1353–1408":"noin 1353–1408","1357–1421":"1357–1421","1379–1443":"1379–1443","1379–Female":"1379–Kuollut","1402–1491":"1402–1491","1353–1408":"1353–1408","1402":"1402","1379":"1379","1357":"1357","1443":"1443","1421":"1421","1353":"1353","about 1378":"noin 1378","1382":"1382","1408":"1408","1491":"1491","about 1353":"noin 1353","Thornham Magna, Suffolk, England":"Thornham Magna, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Stoke by Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Stoke by Ipswich, Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"about 1353–1408":"environ 1353–1408","1357–1421":"1357–1421","1379–1443":"1379–1443","1379–Female":"1379–Décédée","1402–1491":"1402–1491","1353–1408":"1353–1408","1402":"1402","1379":"1379","1357":"1357","1443":"1443","1421":"1421","1353":"1353","about 1378":"environ 1378","1382":"1382","1408":"1408","1491":"1491","about 1353":"environ 1353","Thornham Magna,